\title{Skill Improver}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{"Iteratively reviews and fixes Claude Code skill quality issues until they meet standards. Runs automated fix-review cycles using the skill-reviewer agent. Use to fix skill quality issues, improve skill descriptions, run automated skill review loops, or iteratively refine a skill. Triggers on 'fix my skill', 'improve skill quality', 'skill improvement loop'. NOT for one-time reviews—use /skill-reviewer directly."}

\subtree{
\title{Skill Improvement Methodology}
\p{Iteratively improve a Claude Code skill using the skill-reviewer agent until it meets quality standards.}

\subtree{
\title{Prerequisites}
\p{Requires the \code{\startverb plugin-dev\stopverb} plugin which provides the \code{\startverb skill-reviewer\stopverb} agent.}

\p{Verify it's enabled: run \code{\startverb /plugins\stopverb} — \code{\startverb plugin-dev\stopverb} should appear in the list. If missing, install from the Trail of Bits plugin repository.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Core Loop}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Review} - Call skill-reviewer on the target skill}
\li{\strong{Categorize} - Parse issues by severity}
\li{\strong{Fix} - Address critical and major issues}
\li{\strong{Evaluate} - Check minor issues for validity before fixing}
\li{\strong{Repeat} - Continue until quality bar is met}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use}
\ul{
\li{Improving a skill with multiple quality issues}
\li{Iterating on a new skill until it meets standards}
\li{Automated fix-review cycles instead of manual editing}
\li{Consistent quality enforcement across skills}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{When NOT to Use}
\ul{
\li{\strong{One-time review}: Use \code{\startverb /skill-reviewer\stopverb} directly instead}
\li{\strong{Quick single fixes}: Edit the file directly}
\li{\strong{Non-skill files}: Only works on SKILL.md files}
\li{\strong{Experimental skills}: Manual iteration gives more control during exploration}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Issue Categorization}
\subtree{
\title{Critical Issues (MUST fix immediately)}
\p{These block skill loading or cause runtime failures:}

\ul{
\li{Missing required frontmatter fields (name, description) — Claude cannot index or trigger the skill}
\li{Invalid YAML frontmatter syntax — Parsing fails, skill won't load}
\li{Referenced files that don't exist — Runtime errors when Claude follows links}
\li{Broken file paths — Same as above, leads to tool failures}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Major Issues (MUST fix)}
\p{These significantly degrade skill effectiveness:}

\ul{
\li{Weak or vague trigger descriptions — Claude may not recognize when to use the skill}
\li{Wrong writing voice (second person "you" instead of imperative) — Inconsistent with Claude's execution model}
\li{SKILL.md exceeds 500 lines without using references/ — Overloads context, reduces comprehension}
\li{Missing "When to Use" or "When NOT to Use" sections — Required by project quality standards}
\li{Description doesn't specify when to trigger — Skill may never be selected}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Minor Issues (Evaluate before fixing)}
\p{These are polish items that may or may not improve the skill:}

\ul{
\li{Subjective style preferences — Reviewer may have different taste than author}
\li{Optional enhancements — May add complexity without proportional value}
\li{"Nice to have" improvements — Consider cost-benefit before implementing}
\li{Formatting suggestions — Often valid but low impact}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Minor Issue Evaluation}
\p{Before implementing any minor issue fix, evaluate:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Is this a genuine improvement?} - Does it add real value or just satisfy a preference?}
\li{\strong{Could this be a false positive?} - Is the reviewer misunderstanding context?}
\li{\strong{Would this actually help Claude use the skill?} - Focus on functional improvements}
}

\p{Only implement minor fixes that are clearly beneficial. Skill-reviewer may produce false positives.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Invoking skill-reviewer}
\p{Use the skill-reviewer agent from the plugin-dev plugin. Request a review by asking Claude to:}

\blockquote{Review the skill at [SKILL_PATH] using the plugin-dev:skill-reviewer agent. Provide a detailed quality assessment with issues categorized by severity.}

\p{Replace \code{\startverb [SKILL_PATH]\stopverb} with the absolute path to the skill directory (e.g., \code{\startverb /path/to/plugins/my-plugin/skills/my-skill\stopverb}).}
}

\subtree{
\title{Example Fix Cycle}
\p{\strong{Iteration 1 — skill-reviewer output:}}

\pre{\startverb
Critical: SKILL.md:1 - Missing required 'name' field in frontmatter
Major: SKILL.md:3 - Description uses second person ("you should use")
Major: Missing "When NOT to Use" section
Minor: Line 45 is verbose
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Fixes applied:}}

\ul{
\li{Added name field to frontmatter}
\li{Rewrote description in third person}
\li{Added "When NOT to Use" section}
}

\p{\strong{Iteration 2 — run skill-reviewer again to verify fixes:}}

\pre{\startverb
Minor: Line 45 is verbose
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Minor issue evaluation:} Line 45 communicates effectively as-is. The verbosity provides useful context. Skip.}

\p{\strong{All critical/major issues resolved. Output the completion marker:}}

\pre{\startverb
<skill-improvement-complete>
\stopverb}

\p{Note: The marker MUST appear in the output. Statements like "quality bar met" or "looks good" will NOT stop the loop.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Completion Criteria}
\p{\strong{CRITICAL}: The stop hook ONLY checks for the explicit marker below. No other signal will terminate the loop.}

\p{Output this marker when done:}

\pre{\startverb
<skill-improvement-complete>
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{When to output the marker:}}

\ol{
\li{\strong{skill-reviewer reports "Pass"} or \strong{no issues found} → output marker immediately}
\li{\strong{All critical and major issues are fixed} AND you've verified the fixes → output marker}
\li{\strong{Remaining issues are only minor} AND you've evaluated them as false positives or not worth fixing → output marker}
}

\p{\strong{When NOT to output the marker:}}

\ul{
\li{Any critical issue remains unfixed}
\li{Any major issue remains unfixed}
\li{You haven't run skill-reviewer to verify your fixes worked}
}

\p{The marker is the ONLY way to complete the loop. Natural language like "looks good" or "quality bar met" will NOT stop the loop.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Rationalizations to Reject}
\ul{
\li{"I'll just mark it complete and come back later" - Fix issues now}
\li{"This minor issue seems wrong, I'll skip all of them" - Evaluate each one individually}
\li{"The reviewer is being too strict" - The quality bar exists for a reason}
\li{"It's good enough" - If there are major issues, it's not good enough}
}
}
}